annotations:
[('Late nights in the middle of June', [['June is the first month of summer in the Northern Hemisphere. This relates to the song‚Äôs theme of ‚ÄúHeat Waves.‚Äù

Although the single was originally slated for a mid-June release, it was delayed until the end of the month due to unforeseen, potentially COVID-19-related circumstances.']]), ('Usually I put somethin‚Äô on TV
 So we never think about you and me
 But today I see our reflections clearly
 In Hollywood, layin‚Äô on the screen', [['This is that old cliche where you break up with someone and try to distract yourself with art but you just end up seeing parallels between what‚Äôs on the screen and your own real-life drama. Bayley is alone trying to cope but can‚Äôt stop thinking about the breakup (or his soon-to-be-ex), so he uses entertainment to distract him from his heavy thoughts and feelings.

Could also refer to him seeing the image of them sitting side by side reflected on the screen of the TV set. The attempt to distract from their issues inadvertently forces them to face each other. The TV allows him to see not only literal reflections of their relationship, but also reminds him of the ideals of a happy couple and how his partner needs more than the life they are living due to possible unrequited love.']]), ('Road shimmer wigglin‚Äô the vision
 Heat, heat waves, I‚Äôm swimmin‚Äô in a mirror
 Road shimmer wigglin‚Äô the vision
 Heat, heat waves, I‚Äôm swimmin‚Äô in a‚Äî', [['Dave is referring to a mirage that can occur when asphalt or pavement becomes very hot. Hot air bends light differently than cool air and since the air is rising it creates a shimmery, distorted look that can sometimes look wet.

The imagery of a blurry road ahead of him could represent how his aim or goal in life is blurred by people‚Äôs perceptions of him, making him forget about what he really wants to do in order to make others happy. He‚Äôs mirroring back what they want him to be.']])]

lyrics:
[Verse 1]
Had a great seven-year, white-knuckle ride
Killin' time, flyin' high, as I held on tight
To you, to you

Singin' "Hallelujah" to 'em every night

Ba-da-da-da-da-da

[Verse 2]

Is the black dog out, runnin' wild again
For you, for you?
Tryna stream my way to a better life
But I daydream crash like Vanilla Sky
Do you? Do you?

[Pre-Chorus]
'Cause I'm not gonna lie and say I've been alright
'Cause it feels like I've been livin' upside down

[Chorus]
What can I say? I'm survivin'
Crawlin' out these sheets to see another day
What can I say? I'm survivin'
And I'm gonna be fine, I'm gonna be fine
I think I'll be fine

[Post-Chorus]
Ooh, yeah
Ba-da-da-da-da-da
Ba-da-da-da-da-da
My love, my love
Ooh, yeah
Ba-da-da-da-da-da
Ba-da-da-da-da-da-da
[Chorus]
So what can I say? I'm survivin'
Just crawlin' out these sheets to see another day
Oh, what can I say? I'm survivin'
And I'm gonna be fine, I'm gonna be fine
I think I'll be fine
annotations:
[('Had a great seven-year, white-knuckle ride', [['This verse could be about Bastille itself, and their journey as a band. They released their breakthrough album, Bad Blood, seven years before this song was written and released. The success of that album, which peaked at #1 on the UK Albums Chart, was what started the band‚Äôs international success.']]), ('Tryna stream my way to a better life
 But I daydream crash like Vanilla Sky
 Do you? Do you?', [['This is a reference to the movie Vanilla Sky, in which the main character is revealed to be in a lucid dream. The ‚Äúdaydream crash‚Äù refers to the end of the movie, when the main character opts to exit the lucid dream by leaping off a skyscraper and ‚Äúcrashing‚Äù to the ground.

In the song, this lyric talks about how movies, television, and other streamed media can transport the watcher to a ‚Äúbetter life‚Äù like a daydream, but as hard as one may try to stay in that dream, eventually it all comes crashing down as the watcher (like the character in Vanilla Sky) is pulled back to reality. The song‚Äôs music video also alludes to this, as it uses imagery of skyscrapers, and in the end the character is seen falling to the ground and fading away.

The lyric, ‚ÄúDo you? Do you?‚Äù conveys a sense of desperation; the singer is hoping that their companion experiences the same thing, and that they aren‚Äôt alone in feeling this way.']]), ('Like a thunder cloud in November rain
 Is the black dog out, runnin‚Äô wild again
 For you, for you?', [['These lines are about depression. It gives the imagery of sadness (dark cloud, cold weather, and rain).
‚Äúblack dog‚Äù, according to Cambridge and Oxford dictionary, is used as a metaphor for melancholy or depression.']])]

annotations:
[('‚ÄúI do‚Äù', [['He wants everyone to know how much he loves this person. ‚ÄúI do‚Äù is as in getting married.']]), ('See you standing in your dress
 Swear in front of all our friends', [['You basically have to promise overall when getting married, you have to promise in front of everyone by say ‚ÄòI do‚Äô and become legally married. Like most people, Nialler kind of wants more of his friends to be there at the wedding, of course family should be there, but having friends at your wedding eases the butterflies I guess, so he could be referring to the fact that he might have more friends at the wedding than family so he mentions ‚Äòswearing in front of all our friends there‚Äôll never be another‚Äô he‚Äôs taking an oath to love her and only her for the rest of both their lives.

See you standing in your dress is stereotypically a white dress that‚Äôs worn at a traditional wedding. So Nialler‚Äôs basically more in awe that this woman is the one he‚Äôll live with for the rest of his life and he‚Äôs probably thinking that she looks amazing too. This is more to flatter her.



ps. whoever gets married to Nialler is going to be lucky as hecküíõ‚Ä¶/meüòú']]), ('I can‚Äôt promise picket fences or sunny afternoons', [['Picket fence is a type of low fence made of a row of flat sticks that are pointed at the top and often painted white, which is seen as typical of a comfortable, peaceful, traditional American home. It often symbolizes the ideal middle-class suburban life. So when he says ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt promise picket fences or sunny afternoons‚Äù, he is really saying that he does not know if he will be able to grant her the scenario of a perfect life by American standards.



Sources: Cambridge Dictionary; Wikipedia']]), ('In all your gorgeous colours', [['In an Instagram Live Niall did, he said that this line is one of his favourite lyrics of the song: ‚ÄúThe gorgeous colours meaning personality, like all of your beautiful colours that you possess and not just.. Like when I think about the song Black And White, I don‚Äôt think black and white. I think more colours part.‚Äù']]), ('Now we‚Äôre sittin‚Äô here in your livin‚Äô room
 Tellin‚Äô stories while we share a drink or two
 And there‚Äôs a vision I‚Äôve been holdin‚Äô in my mind
 We‚Äôre sixty-five and you ask
 When did I first know, I always knew', [['Sometime later, maybe the same night as the first verse, or perhaps a different time, he‚Äôs drinking and chatting with somebody.

Niall‚Äôs not all the way present in the conversation, though, as he‚Äôs dreaming about the person in front of him many years later, asking when did he first fall for them.

Niall, in no uncertain terms, tells future them that he always knew that he would fall for them and marry them.']]), ('[Chorus]', [['While it might seem a bit early in their relationship to start dreaming about the future, Niall has no problem doing so in this first chorus.

He knows that this person is who he wants to be with forever. Niall is imagining a wedding in front of both of their friends and family in which he curses, taken aback by something, maybe beauty, maybe shock that he really gets to marry the person he loves.

He swears that this marriage will be his only one and that he‚Äôll love whomever he marries until the end of time.']]), ('That first night, we were standin‚Äô at your door
 Fumblin‚Äô for your keys, then I kissed you
 Ask me if I wanna come inside
 ‚ÄôCause we didn‚Äôt wanna end the night
 Then you took my hand and I followed you', [['As the song begins, Niall is chronicling what is likely the first date between him and somebody else. He‚Äôs dropping them off at their door and they‚Äôre about to go inside when he kisses them.

From that point, it‚Äôs clear that the two don‚Äôt want to part ways, at least for now, so they go inside and spend the rest of the night together.']])]

name: Blinding Lights
lyrics:
[Intro]
Yeah

[Verse 1]
I've been tryna call
I've been on my own for long enough
Maybe you can show me‚ÄÖhow‚ÄÖto love, maybe
I'm‚ÄÖgoing through withdrawals
You don't even have‚ÄÖto do too much
You can turn me on with just a touch, baby

[Pre-Chorus]
I look around and
Sin City's cold and empty (Oh)
No one's around to judge me (Oh)
I can't see clearly when you're gone

[Chorus]
I said, ooh, I'm blinded by the lights
No, I can't sleep until I feel your touch
I said, ooh, I'm drowning in the night
Oh, when I'm like this, you're the one I trust
Hey, hey, hey

[Verse 2]
I'm running out of time
'Cause I can see the sun light up the sky
So I hit the road in overdrive, baby, oh
[Pre-Chorus]
The city's cold and empty (Oh)
No one's around to judge me (Oh)
I can't see clearly when you're gone

[Chorus]
I said, ooh, I'm blinded by the lights
No, I can't sleep until I feel your touch
I said, ooh, I'm drowning in the night
Oh, when I'm like this, you're the one I trust

[Bridge]
I'm just calling back to let you know (Back to let you know)
I could never say it on the phone (Say it on the phone)
Will never let you go this time (Ooh)

[Chorus]
I said, ooh, I'm blinded by the lights
No, I can't sleep until I feel your touch
Hey, hey, hey
Hey, hey, hey

[Outro]
I said, ooh, I'm blinded by the lights
No, I can't sleep until I feel your touch
annotations:
[('You can turn me on with just a touch, baby', [['Abel expresses his great sensitivity towards the girl he‚Äôs with to show he‚Äôs really in love with her, or that he clings to every sign of affection, following what he says in the verse.

Also, even if that mustn‚Äôt be the same person he‚Äôs talking about in this track, Abel is not unfamiliar with this kind of touch. That could imply a reminiscence of feelings he had in his (fictional) past life, and the fact that he‚Äôs very sensitive towards women, and has always been.

This idea is somewhat confirmed in the chorus.']]), ('I‚Äôm running out of time
 ‚ÄôCause I can see the sun light up the sky', [['This line has several meanings:

First, he alludes to Las Vegas again. As mentioned in the pre-chorus of the song, Abel has a special emotional connection to the city. He recalls it here and automatically combines it with the chorus:

No, I can‚Äôt sleep until I feel your touch

Furthermore, Vegas is a city, known for being ‚Äúalive‚Äù at night. Another reason this song‚Äôs story, or the whole album takes place in Vegas are Abel‚Äôs
repeated references of it, adding to the fact, that he feels at home there.

Abel fears, that he won‚Äôt be able to sleep, because he lost his loved one and needs to get her back to finally get sleep. At the end of his journey, he recalls this line. On ‚ÄúFinal Lullaby‚Äù, the last track off the deluxe version of his album After Hours, Abel tries to accept the fact that he won‚Äôt find his love back in that night.

I‚Äôm running out of time
And you‚Äôll always be on my mind

Another explanation could be his habit to be awake late at night, as already mentioned in ‚ÄúAlone Again‚Äù:

I‚Äôm falling only for the night

A possible reason for him being stressed during the day is his fame and popularity. During the day, Abel is blinded by the lights of police cars, but also by flashing camera lights, representing fame. Therefore, he likes to escape into the night, just like in his record ‚ÄúSnowchild‚Äù:

Leaving, leaving into the night
Now a nigga leaving, leaving
Leaving into the night, oh']]), ('I‚Äôm going through withdrawals', [['A ‚Äúwithdrawal‚Äù can both mean the behavior in which one prefers to be alone or also the physical and mental effects experienced when a person stops using a drug. Considering Abel‚Äôs historic of drug abuse, which is largely mentioned in his songs, the second one is more likely.

Moreover, in a 2016 interview with The Guardian he referred to the subject:

When I had nothing to do but make music, it was very heavy. Drugs were a crutch for me.']]), ('So I hit the road in overdrive, baby, oh', [["Here, Abel alludes to his habit of driving over the speed limit, which he has mentioned in several songs in the past, such as on ‚ÄúHeartless,‚Äù‚Äú featured on his fourth studio album, After Hours:

I‚Äôve been dodgin' death in the six-speed

Abel also admits his love for dangerous speeding on his September 2016 single ‚ÄúStarboy‚Äù

100 on the dash get me close to God

‚ÄúBlinding Lights‚Äù was also originally teased in a German Mercedes-Benz commercial, where The Weeknd is shown driving an electric car while the song plays in the background.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C83VEu-yuYA"]]), ('I‚Äôve been tryna call', [['The first line of this song represents Abel‚Äôs vulnerability. A theme explored throughout the rest of this song. On the song ‚ÄúComing Down,‚Äù Abel expresses very similar feelings:

Pick up your phone
The party‚Äôs finished and I want you to know
I‚Äôm all alone

Without drugs, Abel feels a sense of loneliness. This is perhaps Abel‚Äôs truest and most authentic self.']]), ('I said, ooh, I‚Äôm blinded by the lights
 No, I can‚Äôt sleep until I feel your touch
 I said, ooh, I‚Äôm drowning in the night
 Oh, when I‚Äôm like this, you‚Äôre the one I trust
 Hey, hey, hey', [['This song directly follows the outro of ‚ÄúFaith,‚Äù where The Weeknd speaks about being in the back of a police car presumably after an overdose:

I ended up in the back of a flashing car
With the city shining on my face
The lights are blinding me again

The ‚Äúlights‚Äù here not only represent the lights from the police car or the city but also the fame Abel‚Äôs enjoyed for his recording career. From stage lights to paparazzi camera flashes, he‚Äôs been ‚Äúblinded‚Äù by many examples of a wealthy and successful life, and he doesn‚Äôt plan on stopping anytime soon. However, his celebrity life often overshadows his deep personal life. On his 2018 song ‚ÄúPrivilege,‚Äù Abel discusses how many fans and media sources didn‚Äôt believe that he could have a real and genuine relationship with a partner because of his status in fame:

They said our love is just a game, I don‚Äôt care what they say

Nevertheless, his relationship seems to be real and sound, as he claims that it is the only thing that can keep him peacefully inserted in this lifestyle.

Abel also uses a similar line on ‚ÄúSnowchild,‚Äù the fifth track from After Hours:

Leaving, leaving into the night
Now a nigga leaving, leaving
Leaving into the night, oh']]), ('I‚Äôve been on my own for long enough', [['Abel‚Äôs been on his own since around the age of 17 when he dropped out of high school and left home to never come back. This is referenced on many of his songs, like ‚ÄúRolling Stone,‚Äù from his mixtape Thursday, where he said:

‚ÄòCause I‚Äôve been on these streets way too long, too long, too long
Baby, I‚Äôve been on this too long

He‚Äôs also implying that he has been single for quite some time now and has forgotten how to love. From 2015 to 2019 Abel and model Bella Hadid had an on and off relationship, and after spending a few months apart, Abel seems to have lost his ability to love.

To add on, throughout After Hours, Abel plays with the idea of being ‚Äúalone together‚Äù or simply ‚Äúalone‚Äù on songs like ‚ÄúSave Your Tears‚Äù, ‚ÄúFaith,‚Äù and the opening track ‚ÄúAlone Again:‚Äù

‚ÄòCause I don‚Äôt know if I can be alone again
I don‚Äôt know if I can be alone again']]), ('I look around and
 Sin City‚Äôs cold and empty (Oh)
 No one‚Äôs around to judge me (Oh)
 I can‚Äôt see clearly when you‚Äôre gone', [['Las Vegas is nicknamed ‚ÄúSin City‚Äù due to the city‚Äôs overwhelming presence of crime, drugs, and sexual promiscuity‚Äîall important themes throughout The Weeknd‚Äôs career. He also explores hedonism on his August 2011 song ‚ÄúHeaven or Las Vegas.‚Äù

Abel experienced emptiness and heartbreak when he was briefly separated from Bella Hadid in 2019. The two have since reunited and emotionally completed The Weeknd.

Abel previously touched upon his need for Bella on his November 2019 single, ‚ÄúHeartless‚Äù:

You just came back in my life
You never gave up on me (Why don‚Äôt you?)
I‚Äôll never know what you see (Why won‚Äôt you?)
I don‚Äôt do well when alone (Oh yeah)']]), ('I‚Äôm just calling back to let you know (Back to let you know)
 I could never say it on the phone (Say it on the phone)
 Will never let you go this time (Ooh)', [['This line is very similar to the song ‚ÄúHeartless,‚Äù released just days before this song. Here, Abel describes how his love for whom is presumed to be Bella Hadid is much stronger than he can say on the phone to her. This is different than the feelings Abel has shown in previous albums, with his typical themes usually revolving around never showing love towards anyone he is with and only using them for sex.']])]

It‚Äôs a terrible food. It‚Äôs one of those things that we gotta start eating. It‚Äôs a superfood. When we were writing the lyrics, we were trying to figure out how to encompass adulthood in one word, and it was quinoa.‚Äù']]), ('Come hang (Come hang)
 Let‚Äôs go out with a bang!', [['AJR says Lets Go out with a Bang! But its by far not their last song. They admitted that they have at least one last album in store in their ‚ÄúHow we made the Neotheater‚Äù Video https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y-6mhrYiacs

‚ÄúA lot of you asked how we made that old timey orchestral sound- We can‚Äôt tell you you that because its a big piece in our next album.‚Äù
Ryan said.
The Band has repeatedly said that with their new album The OK Orchestra, they are going to do so many new sounds. With the great success of Neotheater and the difference its music has from The Click, this could just be saying they‚Äôre done with  the pop that they have repeatedly used. They might just be saying they‚Äôre going out with a Bang. They are coming out of their skin and knocking down all barriers we thought they were held back by by changing everything. The difference between bang and My play are exponentially different in the base that it is getting way more personal and deep, and more changes.']]), ('So ooh-dee-la-dee-doe
 Yeah, come on here we go', [['At this part in the music video, the people are in uniform and are moving all together. This shows that they‚Äôre going along with the system with everyone else. Then, they start moving backwards and have shocked expressions, meaning that they don‚Äôt want to be part of the system anymore because they know what it‚Äôs really like.']]), ('I‚Äôm not feeling grown', [['This lyric is a reference to their song ‚ÄúNext Up Forever.‚Äù Following the theme of being afraid to grow up and clinging to childhood, the song  specifically references these lines:

‚ÄúI know I gotta grow up sometimes
But I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôm ready yet‚Äù']]), ('I‚Äôm way too young to lie here forever', [['This line is a reference to another AJR song, ‚ÄúKarma‚Äù. One of the lines in ‚ÄúKarma‚Äù is: ‚ÄúWait, don‚Äôt go away, can I lie here forever?‚Äù. The theme of Neotheater and ‚ÄúBang!‚Äù has been growing up, so this line implies AJR has realized that they have a whole life ahead of them and will need to figure some things out on their own.']]), ('Bang! Bang! Bang! (Here we go!)', [['This vocal snippet is from one of New York City‚Äôs subway system announcers, Charlie Pellet, who is credited as a background vocalist on the track.']]), ('Come hang (Come hang)', [['This lyric is a part of a song from AJR‚Äôs Click album: Come Hang Out, where they can‚Äôt hang out because they are so busy with their music. Here, it seems like they are going to be done with music and now they have time to hang out with their friends.']]), ('Been a hell of a ride
 But I‚Äôm thinking it‚Äôs time to go', [['AJR has mentioned before in ‚ÄúBeats‚Äù and ‚ÄúFinale (Can‚Äôt Wait to See What You Do Next)‚Äù that they are afraid they won‚Äôt stay big for long. If they have the chance to choose how they go out, they‚Äôd rather go out big and loud than disappearing into obscurity.

This is shown in these lines from ‚ÄúBeats‚Äù:

What if some day, you say, ‚ÄúWho the hell is that?‚Äù
Okay, this all could be over by the next day

and these lines from ‚ÄúFinale (Can‚Äôt Wait to See What You Do Next)‚Äù:

If it‚Äôs my final album
And if I am forgotten
I hope I made you smile
That‚Äôs all I ever wanted']]), ('(Metronome!)', [['Adding the metronome is a nod to the artistic style used throughout The Click. These sounds specifically have been used in ‚ÄúCome Hang Out‚Äù and the ‚ÄúOverture‚Äù of The Click.']])]
